@node "Introduction" "Control Panel Guide - Introduction"
@{b}@{fg shine}Control Panel Version 6 @{u}@{fg text}

Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

Control Panel is an Arexx program which allows control of the basic AmiTCP
functions through an easy to use interface.

The Control Panel package also allows various applications to be run by
clicking on the relevant buttons. Various GUI frontends for AmitTCP
utilities have been produced by myself and are included with this package.

Control Panel itself was written as a utility so that I could easily start
and stop AmiTCP without having to resort to typing commands at the shell or
having to set up a menu on my toolbar.

The front ends were written as I was tired at looking at GUI frontends for
Mac utilities in .net. The Amiga is a multitasking GUI computer so all
utilities should be able to be used in this way. Various other parts of the
package were written as I found a need for them, i.e. the scripts for
posting news from GRn.

This version of Control Panel allows the user to

- Start/Stop AmiTCP @ - Connect/Disconnect from the net @ - Change Users @ -
Automatically run programs at a set time @ - Run the following types of
programs

@{"Mail" link "mail" 0}, @{"News" link "News" 0}, @{"FTP" link "News" 0},@{"WWW" link "www" 0}, @{"Gopher" link "gopher" 0}, @{"IRC" link "IRC" 0}, @{"Archie" link "Archie" 0}, @{"Telnet" link "Telnet" 0}, @{"Finger" link "finger" 0},
@{"Ping" link "CPIS" 0}, @{"Dearchivers" link "GuiArc" 0}, and a @{"Newsgroup editor" link "NewsEd" 0}.

These programs can be started by just clicking on a button, using the menus
or using the hotkeys. For any program which has not got a gui interface and
needs user input i.e. Ping, Traceroute etc.., I have included a GUI front end
for these programs. 

Their is also a total of 3 user definable buttons and unlimited other user
definable menu choices, as well as menus for changing to pre-defined users
, for using multiple POP's and for editing files.

A status window, shows various details such as user name, real name, date,
time, and how long you've been connected. 

A log file (uuspool:cp.log) is created recording details of every
connection. This file is in Ncomm format which can be read by phonebill
analysing programs such as Phonebill, a BT template for Phonebill is
available to registered users.

Due to the time spent on this project, and my current financial position,
CP6 is @{"shareware" link "register" 0}. All registered users of CP5 will get CP6 free of charge.
@endnode

@node "installation" "Control Panel Guide - Installation"
@{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

Double click on the ControlPanel installation icon and let the script do all
the hard work. You have to enter some configuration details about your
system setup, and what programs you usually use when on the internet.

@{b}Configuration File@{ub}

There are now several configuration files, these are all stored in cp:prefs
except for the main file which is s:cp.config. The files may be changed
manually, but their is an included preferences program that will change them
for you.

@{b}Parameters@{ub}

There are several options which can only be selected by including parameters
 when calling cp6.exe. To change these options you will need to edit the
file ControlPanel6 and add any necessary parameters. For most peoples needs
they will not need to alter this file, but it does allow a bit more
flexibility.

FONT fontsize - allows you to use a larger font than the std size 8,
                providing the control panel can still fit on the screen.

MINI          - Start CP in single strip / mini mode

SUPERHIRES    - Tells CP that you are using a super hires screen

INTERLACED    - Tells CP that you are using an interlaced screen

NOMENU        - Menus are not displayed, saves time and memory

These options can be combined e.g

run >nil: cp6.exe FONT 20 MINI SUPERHIRES INTERLACED NOMENU

would make CP6 use a size 20 font, start in mini mode and have no menu
items.

The SUPERHIRES and INTERLACED relax the Control Panel size checking
routines, so may cause a crash if you specify them when they are not needed.

If a font size is specified that won't allow Control Panel to fit on th
screen, a smaller font will be used, this font being the biggest that will
allow Control Panel to fit.

This is all you should need to know about installation, if not E-Mail Me!
@endnode

@node "Buttons" "Control Panel Guide - Main Control Panel"
@{b}@{u}Main Panel@{ub}@{uu}

On start-up you will be presented with the main @{b}Control Panel@{ub} requester
which will look something like this :@{fg shine}

   ___________________________________________________________________  @{b}@{fg text}
   @{ub}@{fg shine}|                                                                  |
   |    __________________________________________________________    |
   |   | User name :           Real Name :                        |   |
   |   |                                                          |   |
@{"Status Display" link "StatusDisplay" 0}
   |   | Date :            Time :            Connected:           |   |
   |   |__________________________________________________________|   |
   |                                                                  |
   | @{"Start" link "Start" 0}@{"Stop" link "Stop" 3} @{"Connect" link "Connect" 6}@{"Disconnect" link "Disconnect" 6}  @{"Change User" link "ChangeUser" 0}  @{"Prefs" link "Prefs" 0}  @{"Mode" link "mode" 0}  @{"End" link "Quit" 0}|
   |                                                                  |
   | @{"EMAIL" link "Mail" 0} @{"NEWS" link "News" 0} @{"FTP" link "FTP" 0} @{"WWW" link "WWW" 0} @{"GOPHER" link "Gopher" 0} @{"IRC" link "IRC" 0} @{"ARCHIE" link "Archie" 0} @{"TELNET" link "Telnet" 0} @{"FINGER" link "Finger" 0} @{"CPIS" link "cpis" 0}
   | @{"UUXT" link "UUXT" 0} @{"DEARC" link "GUIARC" 0} @{"NEWS ED" link "newsed" 0} @{"User Opt1" link "Options" 0} @{"User Opt2" link "options" 0} @{"User Opt3" link "options" 0}           |
   |                                                                  |
   |__________________________________________________________________|

Just click on the buttons to find out more.
@endnode

@node "start" "Control Panel Guide - Start Amitcp"
@{b}@{u}Start@{ub}@{uu}

This option starts AmiTCP by running @{"Amiconnect" link "amitcp:docs/amiconnect.guide/main" 0} or by a script/program that
you have configured in the @{"main prefs" link "Prefs/Main" 0} program.
@endnode

@node "stop" "Control Panel Guide - Stop Amitcp"
@{b}@{u}Stop@{ub}@{uu}

This option stops AmiTCP by running @{"Amiconnect" link "amitcp:docs/amiconnect.guide/main" 0} or the program/script that
you have chosen in the @{"main prefs" link "Prefs/Main" 0} program. You may need to run this in order
to free some memory, for use with non AmiTCP applications. If you do stop
AmiTCP you must remember to restart it by using @{"Start" link "start" 0}, before running any
program that requires AmiTCP.
@endnode

@node "Connect" "Control Panel Guide - Connect To Net"
@{b}@{u}Connect@{ub}@{uu}

The default action for this button is to run @{"Amiconnect" link "amitcp:docs/Amiconnect/main" 0}, but you may change
this by altering the values using the @{"main prefs" link "Prefs/Main" 0} program.
@endnode

@node "Disconnect" "Control Panel Guide - Disconnect From Net"
@{b}@{u}Disconnect@{ub}@{uu}

Disconnects from host computer, either using @{"Amiconnect" link "amitcp:docs/amiconnect.guide" 0} or the program which
you have chosen in the @{"main prefs" link "Prefs/Main" 0} program.
@endnode

@node "Changeuser" "Control Panel Guide - Change User"
@{b}@{u}Change User@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Setting Up A New User@{ub}

The @{bg fill}@{fg shine}listview gadget@{bg back}@{fg text}is where all the names of the defined users are
shown, when selected the details for that user are shown in the string
gadgets to the right of the display.

@{bg shine}User Name:@{bg back}

This is where you enter the user name of the user you are defining, this
will be stored as env:user and will appear on CP5's user menu.

@{bg shine}Real Name:@{bg back}

This is the realname associated with the user being defined, it will be used
to set the realname environment variable.

@{bg shine}Organisation:@{bg back}

This is an organisation string which you can assign to a user, this will set
the organization environment variable.

@{bg shine}IRC Nickname:@{bg back}

This is the nickname that user usually uses when using IRC.

@{bg shine}Home Directory:@{bg back}

This is the directory where all that users files are usually kept, clicking
on the @{"F" link ""} button will bring up a file requester.

@{"Edit Signature" link ""}:

This brings up the text editor and allows you to edit that users signature
file.

@{b}User Menu Options@{ub}

To change to a new user just select the new user from the user menu, or use
the change user button and select the new user from the listview.
@endnode

@node "Mail" "Control Panel Guide - Electronic Mail"
@{b}@{u}E-Mail@{ub}@{uu}

Runs the mail program that you have configured using the @{"Prefs/Programs" link "Preferences"} menu item.

The default/recommended program is Admail, which is available in the
comm/mail drawer on Aminet.

@endnode

@node "News" "Control Panel Guide - Usenet News"
@{b}@{u}News@{ub}@{uu}

Runs the News program which you have configured using the @{"prefs/programs" link "preferences"} menu.
I suggest that you use @{"Grn" link "grn.guide/main" 0} along with the postnews script included with this package.
@endnode

@node "Ftp" "Control Panel Guide - File Transfer Protocol"
@{b}@{u}File Transfer Protocol@{ub}@{uu}

This runs the graphical FTP client you have configured using the
@{"prefs/programs" link "preferences"}

One such program is GUI-FTP, see @{"GUI-FTP.guide" link "GUI-FTP.guide/main" 0} for more details.
@endnode

@node "WWW" "Control Panel Guide - World Wide Web"
@{b}@{u}World Wide Web@{ub}@{uu}

This runs a World Wide Web browser, such as Amosaic or Alynx.
You can configure this using the @{"prefs/programs" link "preferences"}
@endnode

@node "IRC" "Control Panel Guide - Internet Relay Chat"
@{b}@{u}Internet Relay Chat@{ub}@{uu}
Runs an IRC client, at the moment I only know of one graphical IRC client
this being Grapevine.

You can configure this using the @{"prefs/programs" link "preferences"}
@endnode

@node "Archie" "Control Panel Guide - Archie"
@{b}@{u}Archie@{ub}@{uu}

Runs a graphical Archie client, such as my graphical front end for Archie, called
Arfir which now allows downloading of files.
See included @{"Arfir.Guide" link "amitcp:docs/arfir.guide/main" 0} for more details.

You can configure this using the @{"prefs/programs" link "preferences"}

My front end is now part of a separate package consisting of Newsed and
Arfir (a gui frontend for Archie), and should be available on Aminet as
aminet:/comm/tcp/NewsedArfir.lha

@endnode

@node "Telnet" "Control Panel Guide - Telnet"
@{b}@{u}Telnet@{ub}@{uu}

Runs my graphical front end for telnet.

This frontend now allows you to store all the addresses you sometimes telnet
to, so that you don't have to remember them. There is no limit to the number
of addresses but please note that if you have hundreds of address it will
take a little while to load all the details in.

@{b}Entering A New Site@{ub}

Click on New to remove any existing text, type the name of the telnet
service (this needs to be a short phrase to remind you what that server is
used for), then enter the telnet address (irc.demon.co.uk) and then the port
number if known or required (6667), then press the store site button.

@{b}Removing A Site@{ub}

Click on the sites name in the listview gadget and then hit the delete
 site button.@{b}

Telnetting To A Site@{ub}

Click on the sites name in the listview gadget and then hit the telnet
button, the program called telnet will then be called. If your telnet client
is not called telnet e-mail me and I will send you a customised patch,
alternatively rename your client Telnet.
@endnode

@node "finger" "Control Panel Guide - Finger"
@{b}@{u}Finger@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Entering A New Site@{ub}

Click on New to remove any existing text, type the name of the finger
server (this needs to be a short phrase to remind you what that server is
used for), then enter the finger user name (the bit before the @{b} @ @{ub}i.e. motd) and then the host name
(gate.demon.co.uk), then press the store site button.

@{b}Removing A Site@{ub}

Click on the sites name in the listview gadget and then hit the delete
 site button.@{b}

Fingering A Site@{ub}

Click on the sites name in the listview gadget and then hit the finger
button, the program called finger will then be called. If your finger client
is not called finger e-mail me and I will send you a customised patch,
alternatively rename your client Finger.

@endnode

@node "GuiArc" "Control Panel Guide - Dearchiver"
@{b}@{u}Gui-Arc@{ub}@{uu}

Gui-Arc is a graphical front end for various archivers such as LHA, this
program is available on Aminet. Please read its document for further
information.

Other GUI based archivers/dearchivers may be used, instead of Gui-Arc.

@endnode

@node "UUXT" "Control Panel Guide - UUXT"
@{b}@{u}UUXT@{ub}@{uu}

UUXT is a utility which changes binary files which have been sent via Usenet
or E-Mail into programs that can be run.

This option requires the program UUxT-GUI or similar to run.

@endnode

@node "NewsEd" "Control Panel Guide - Newsgroup Editor"
@{b}@{u}News Editor@{ub}@{uu}

This runs my newsgroup editing program or an alternative to allow easier
adding and deleting of newsgroups.

See @{"NewsEd Instructions" link "newsgroupeditor.guide/main" 0} For More Details

This program is now part of a separate package consisting of Newsed and
Arfir (a gui frontend for Archie), and should be available on Aminet as
aminet:/comm/tcp/NewsedArfir.lha

@endnode

@node "auto" "Control Panel Guide - Auto"
@{b}@{u}Auto @{uu}@{ub}

Allows a program or script to be run at a particular time.

Set the time you want the program to be run at by using the sliders,
the time selected will be shown on the line below the seconds slider.

Then enter the program name in the program string entry gadget, or use
the file selector @{"F" link ""}.

Then enter any parameters that program requires.

Finally press start to run the selected program at the designated time, or
press cancel to abort.

-----------------------------------------------------------
|                                                         |
|      Hours  @{bg fill}                      |                  @{bg back}   |
|                                                         |
|    Minutes  @{bg fill}          |                              @{bg back}   |
|                                                         |
|    Seconds  @{bg fill}                             |           @{bg back}   |
|                                                         |
|             @{bg highlight}   Run Program At  hh:mm:ss              @{bg back}   |
|                                                         |
|                                                         |
|    Program  @{bg shine}                                     @{bg back}  @{"F" link ""}   |
|                                                         |
| Parameters  @{bg shine}                                         @{bg back}   |
|                                                         |
|                        @{"Start" link ""}  @{"Cancel" link ""}                  |
|                                                         |
-----------------------------------------------------------

@endnode

@node "gopher" "Control Panel Guide - Gopher"
@{b}@{u}Gopher@{ub}@{uu}

This option allows you to use an Amiga gopher client, such as AGopher.

Gopherring allows you to find various resources and information by just
clicking on particular words, it is similar to the World Wide Web, but is
totally text based.

@endnode

@node "quit" "Control Panel Guide - Quit/End"
@{b}@{u}Quit/End@{ub}@{uu}

This option quits Control Panel and saves the current position if save
position is enabled.

@endnode

@node "progs" "Control Panel Guide - Recommended Programs"
@{b}@{u}Programs Suggested to Fully Utilise Control Panel@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}From ftp.demon.co.uk@{ub}

@{u}World Wide Web Browser - Amosaic@{uu}

/pub/amiga/mosaic/Mosaic_1.2_AmiTCP.lha

Currently the only Amiga WWW browser, version 1.4b (2.0) is available from
Mosaic's home. This directory /pub/amiga/mosaic also contains various
utilities which you may need to get mosaic working.

@{b}From src.doc.ic.ac.uk / Any Aminet Site@{ub}

@{u}EMail - Admail@{uu}

/pub/aminet/comm/mail/ADMail.lha

@{u}News - Grn@{uu}

/pub/aminet/comm/news/GRn_2.1a.lha

@{u}FTP - GUI-FTP@{uu}

/pub/aminet/comm/tcp/Gui_FTP.lha

@{u}IRC - Grapevine@{uu}

/pub/aminet/comm/net/grapevine.lha

@{u}Archie - Archie@{uu}

/pub/aminet/comm/tcp/archie38.1.lha

@{u}Gopher - Gopher@{uu}

/pub/aminet/comm/tcp/gopher.lha

@{u}Mail Receiving Daemon - AmiTCPsmtpd@{uu}

/pub/aminet/comm/tcp/AmiTCPsmtpd.lha

@{u}UUxT - GUI@{uu}

/pub/aminet/util/arc/uuxt30b.lha

@{u}Archiver - GuiArc@{uu}

/pub/aminet/util/arc/GuiArc.lha

These are only suggested programs, you may use any programs you like.

The following programs are written by me and are designed to integrate 
directly with Control Panel 6.

@{b}Arfir & Newsed Package@{ub}

ftp://src.doc.ic.ac.uk/pub/aminet/comm/tcp/NewsedArfir.lha

This package consists of 2 main programs and some other useful scripts.

@{u}Arfir@{uu}

Arfir is a GUI front end for Archie, which allows you to select parameters
through an easy to use interface and once the archie search has been completed,
it allows you to download or view the files via an easy to use listview
selector. This program requires FTPGet to work.

@{u}Newsed@{uu}
Newsed is a GUI editor for you uulib:newsgroups file, it allows you to edit
the file using simple requesters and allows you to choose new groups from
a separate group list such as your providers active file. You may either
choose individual groups or use the import function to selectively choose
groups, e.g. you can select all the groups which have Amiga in them.
Newsed also allows you to write a brief description about the newsgroups so
that you can remember what the focus of that groups is, it also allows
unique signatures for each groups when used in conjunction with the 
provided postnews scripts and GRn.

@{b}AmiConnect@{ub}

ftp://src.doc.ic.ac.uk/pub/aminet/comm/tcp/Amiconnect.lha

This program is a dialler script which can be easily aborted and is easy to
configure. This program replaces any startnet and/or link scripts as well 
as any dialler program, all the configuration is done through a gui 
configuration interface, there is no need to edit several file.

Amiconnect should blend with AmiTCP4 and CP6 to allow an easier connection to the internet.

A version of amiconnect is included with Control Panel 6, and is installed
as default.

@{b}New Programs@{ub}
Over the last few months (summer 95) several new programs have been developped
which are in my opinion very good. These programs are not yet 100% finished
and may contain some minor problems, but I advise you to take a look at
them.

@{fg shine}DAFTP@{fg text}
A new GUI FTP program which allows multiple download and uploads and
includes a hotlist for your favourite sites. It is very good but still in
Beta release. It can be obtained from ftp.warped.com in the /pub/amiga/daftp
drawer, the latest version of Grapevine is also at this site.

@{fg shine}AMIrc{fg text}
A new IRC client which uses MUI but is stable, it works well and looks very
nice, it is only currently on alpha release so some facilities are not yet
implemented. Despite this it is operational and comparable to Grapevine.

It is available from wade1.ab.umd.edu in the support directory.

@{fg shine}Thor2.1@{fg text}
Thor is an excellent Mail/News program, this is a release version although
bugfixes and improvements are being made as necessary.
Thos is available on aminet in the comm/mail drawer, get the main program
file and the inet module plus any bugfixes.

If you want some advice on setting Thor up with CP5, please e-mail me.

@{fg shine}FTP Mount@{fg text}
FTP mount is a device driver which allows you to use FTP via the standard
amiga interface, both amiga dos and workbench. This is an excellent program
although it can be slower than DaFTP at times. It is in the comm/tcp drawer
on Aminet.

@endnode

